<h1>Section 2 — Current JIRA &amp; ServiceNow Integrations</h1>
<p>How JIRA and ServiceNow connect to the pipeline today — what works, what is manual, and what gaps exist.</p>

<table>
  <colgroup>
    <col style="width: 50%;" />
    <col style="width: 50%;" />
  </colgroup>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <th><strong>JIRA Today</strong> — Test management &amp; sprint tracking</th>
      <th><strong>ServiceNow (SNOW) Today</strong> — Change request lifecycle</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>
        <p><strong>Sprint stories tracked manually</strong></p>
        <p>JIRA boards manage sprint stories but there is no automated link between a JIRA ticket and the code changes (PR / commit) that deliver it. Developers include ticket IDs in branch names and commit messages by convention — no platform enforcement.</p>
        <ac:structured-macro ac:name="status"><ac:parameter ac:name="colour">Red</ac:parameter><ac:parameter ac:name="title">Manual Convention</ac:parameter></ac:structured-macro>
      </td>
      <td>
        <p><strong>SNOW CR auto-created by pipeline</strong> ✓</p>
        <p>When a PR is raised to the Prod branch, the Jenkins pipeline automatically creates a ServiceNow Change Request. This is the most mature automation in the current pipeline. JET IDs are linked to the commit hash at this stage.</p>
        <ac:structured-macro ac:name="status"><ac:parameter ac:name="colour">Blue</ac:parameter><ac:parameter ac:name="title">Automated</ac:parameter></ac:structured-macro>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>
        <p><strong>No automated deployment status update</strong></p>
        <p>After a feature is deployed to production, the JIRA story status must be updated manually by the developer or release manager. No pipeline event triggers a JIRA status change.</p>
        <ac:structured-macro ac:name="status"><ac:parameter ac:name="colour">Red</ac:parameter><ac:parameter ac:name="title">Manual Update</ac:parameter></ac:structured-macro>
      </td>
      <td>
        <p><strong>Peer review and approval are manual</strong></p>
        <p>Despite the CR being auto-created, the peer review of the Change Task and the final change approval in SNOW are both manual checkpoints. Bottlenecks here block the deployment window.</p>
        <ac:structured-macro ac:name="status"><ac:parameter ac:name="colour">Red</ac:parameter><ac:parameter ac:name="title">Manual Checkpoint</ac:parameter></ac:structured-macro>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>
        <p><strong>Test evidence compiled manually</strong></p>
        <p>Test results live in JET, test cases in JIRA, and regression results in the pipeline log. The test exit report must be manually assembled from multiple sources. No single traceability chain from story to evidence.</p>
        <ac:structured-macro ac:name="status"><ac:parameter ac:name="colour">Red</ac:parameter><ac:parameter ac:name="title">Manual Assembly</ac:parameter></ac:structured-macro>
      </td>
      <td>
        <p><strong>CR status not a hard pipeline gate</strong></p>
        <p>The pipeline does not wait for SNOW CR approval before allowing deployment to proceed. This depends on the team manually checking the CR status before merging the Prod PR — no hard gate exists.</p>
        <ac:structured-macro ac:name="status"><ac:parameter ac:name="colour">Yellow</ac:parameter><ac:parameter ac:name="title">Gap — No Gate</ac:parameter></ac:structured-macro>
      </td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

